This initiative delivers a comprehensive digital engineering ecosystem, encompassing a cloud-based Digital Engineering (DE)
environment and a government-owned software development platform that integrates Artificial Intelligence (AI), Machine Learning
(ML), and a Development/Security/Operations (DevSecOps) pipeline. It employs a Digital Twin technology development approach
to enhance system design and analysis.
The DE costs include software engineering (SE) licenses for Product Lifecycle Management (PLM) software, Model-Based
Systems Engineering (MBSE) SysML modeling tools, data management and analysis tools, and modeling and simulation
software. DevSecOps costs cover the infrastructure necessary to support the XM30 Software Pathway program, including two
vendors developing software within a government-furnished cloud environment. These costs are based on the licenses and
pipelines required to oversee and develop XM30 software using an agile DevSecOps methodology. Integration costs include
the development of Application Programming Interfaces (APIs) to connect PLM software with various government-owned and
commercial tools. This effort also supports future cloud security enhancements, data backups, and data archiving.
Additionally, this initiative funds the Virtual Software-In-The-Loop (VSIL) environment hosted within the Digital Acquisition
Environment (DAE). The VSIL environment virtualizes computing hardware and software, including graphics and memory systems
associated with vehicle designs. Virtual Machines (VMs) within the DAE emulate the computing hardware specifications of the
physical systems. Software from the DevSecOps environment integrates into these VMs to virtualize computing machines,
develop test software to evaluate computing resource constraints, and assess interactions among virtual machines. These VMs
are instantiated using scripts based on the hardware specifications defined in the vehicle's model-based definition. The VSIL
environment enables early and frequent virtual testing of computing hardware, reducing uncertainty in hardware performance and
improving overall system reliability and efficiency.
