B. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                                       FY 2025    FY 2026      FY 2027
As of 30 September 2011, program management is provided by the Defense Logistics Agency (DLA), including responsibilities
related to the stewardship of governmental funds provided in DoW appropriations to address the Department's long-term
objectives in supporting Humanitarian Assistance and Disaster Relief (HA/DR) operations, Defense Support to Civil Authorities
(DSCA), and enabling resilience of the Department's warfighting mission amidst an evolving operating environment.
PDC serves as a global leader in risk intelligence, hazard monitoring, disaster early warning, and advanced analytics. PDC and
its DisasterAWARE technology – including RAPIDS, a customized CUI version for DoW – deliver several unique capabilities
for global situational awareness and decision support to DoW, the State Department, other U.S. government agencies, and
international partners. Harnessing the power of artificial intelligence, PDC provides tailored updates that inform real-time response
to natural and man-made hazards (e.g. extreme weather, civil disorder, biological threats, etc.) that could harm the American
people or disrupt the American economy.
In addition, PDC’s hazard monitoring and predictive modeling capabilities are essential to advancing U.S. priorities in the 2025
National Security Strategy and the 2026 National Defense Strategy. These include ensuring resilient national infrastructure that
can withstand natural disasters, facilitating movement-and-maneuver route assessment to ensure DoW access to key terrain,
informing military construction and posture decisions in the Indo-Pacific to help erect a strong denial defense, and assessing
supply chain vulnerability to supercharge the Defense Industrial Base. These capabilities support Expeditionary Advanced Base
Operations (EABO), distributed maritime operations, and broader joint force maneuver, sustainment, and access in contested
environments. Together, PDC’s unique technologies and services strengthen national defense capabilities and ensure the
resilience of the U.S. homeland by informing joint planning, contingency response, and emergency/disaster response operations.
Multiple components within the Office of the Secretary of War (OSW), the Joint Staff, Combatant Commands (CCMDs), Services,
and other USG agencies rely on PDC’s capabilities to execute a broad range of mission assurance, HA/DR, and DSCA objectives.
PDC's evolving capabilities are reshaping its value proposition across the defense and humanitarian sectors. For over 30 years,
PDC has operationalized the world's most comprehensive disaster and risk intelligence ecosystem by integrating global hazard
monitoring, validated scientific modeling, AI-enabled analytics, and operational decision support in a single platform trusted by
combatant commands, federal agencies, emergency offices, and international partners.
Today, PDC is expanding beyond traditional disaster response into strategic risk assessment and analytical capabilities that
directly inform data-driven decision-making for combatant commands and national security planners. Recent innovations include
analytical products addressing "Green-White" networks to identify and counter malign actors, critical minerals analysis assessing
supply chain vulnerabilities, and national fragility indices quantifying evolving security and stability landscapes. These capabilities
exemplify PDC's maturing Global Risk and Vulnerability Assessment (RVA) program, which leverages CCMD partnerships to
support and (externally) fund National Disaster Preparedness Baseline Assessment (NDPBA) projects worldwide.
This evolution has transformed PDC from a disaster monitoring platform into a comprehensive risk intelligence capability
addressing the full spectrum of strategic challenges, from natural hazards to economic security to emerging transnational threats.

