B. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                                FY 2025    FY 2026      FY 2027
- Overhauled and modernized DisasterAWARE mapping engine and user interface functions to take advantage of newer
technologies for a better and more effective visualization of data
- Modernized multi-hazard detection and processing (service-based architecture) to allow for better coverage and scaling
- Deployed RAPIDS in the cloud with improved accessibility and uptime
- Deployed AI Hazard Finder, a full-scale AI platform to increase hazard coverage from reading and analyzing unstructured data
(e.g., global news), gaining internal efficiency by reducing manual work, and replacing two vendor-supplied data sources, saving
$75K in annual subscription fees
- Implemented new APIs supporting access to expanded global critical infrastructure layers, analytics, and AIM data for full
integration across all systems and products
- Expanded hazard coverage and analysis by adding data from several official national meteorological offices, such as those from
India, China, Canada, and Australia
- Improved AI-related infrastructure by configuring complex GPU hardware (acquired through previous UFRs) and software to
securely retain (and isolate) sensitive training data and models from those operating in open and connected environments
- Updated and enhanced situational awareness briefs
- Automated several custom analytical products for advanced decision support for the stakeholders
- Reviewed, assessed compliance, and revised cybersecurity measures aligned with DoW’s related directives

PDC Stakeholder Engagement and Support:
- Supported four major disaster activations with over 300 custom products, including major support for USSOUTHCOM for the
humanitarian assistance operations regarding Hurricane Melissa
- Covered well over 100 large global disasters, supporting various CCMDs and stakeholders with informational and situational
awareness products
- Conducted 66 formalized training sessions to include 450 DoW/CCMD, and 760 partner nation trainees
- Contributed to and participated in 21 multi-national exercises, including nine major USINDOPACOM and USSOUTHCOM
exercises, such as Tradewinds, Pacific Partnership, Jaguar Sentine, and JTF-Bravo J3 Exercise, to name a few
- Provided critical support to USSOUTHCOM J33 CAT/JOIC during steady-state and HA/DR response operations, including
training and use of DisasterAWARE/RAPIDS by SC and JTF-B
- Expanded PDC coordination with USAFRICOM J5 and JOC in direct support to increasing situational awareness for human-
induced/conflict and natural hazard events in the AOR
- Expanded direct analysis support to USAFRICOM J5 for Strategic Competition, including products for IUU-F and Critical
Minerals
- Expanded online and train-the trainer programs

