Description: The Small Business Innovation Research (SBIR) and Small Business Technology Transfer (STTR) programs are

RDT&E Management Support

C. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                                   FY 2025    FY 2026       FY 2027
designed to provide small, high-tech businesses and academic institutions the opportunity to propose radical, innovative, high-risk
approaches to address existing and emerging national security threats; thereby supporting DARPA's overall strategy to enable
fundamental discoveries and technological breakthroughs that provide new military capabilities.

FY 2026 Plans:
- Once reauthorized, Small Business Program Office (SBPO) will implement any new legislative changes and processes outlined
within the new SBIR/STTR Policy Directive.
- Once reauthorized, SBPO will continue to utilize DoW's yearlong BAA to release SBIR/STTR topics on a Just-in-Time basis via
DoW's monthly release schedule.
- Once reauthorized, and if still applicable, SBPO will continue to release an SBIR and/or STTR Open topic in accordance with
the 2022 SBIR/STTR Reauthorization Act. Lessons learned from the FY 2025 release will be identified and implemented for FY
2026.
- Once reauthorized, and if still applicable, SBPO will continue and/or adjust in accordance with new legislation its Due Diligence
Program Business Assessment Program, taking lessons learned from FY 2025 and improving and streamlining them in FY 2026.
- Once reauthorized, will continue to leverage DARPA SBIR/STTR topics in support of larger DARPA Programs to the highest
extent possible to ensure successful transition of SBIR/STTR technologies.
- Once reauthorized, SBPO will continue to utilize various funding pathways available to the SBIR/STTR programs. This includes,
Phase I, Phase II, Direct to Phase II, co-funds, cross agency awards, Phase II Enhancements, and SBIR XL Pilot.
- Once reauthorized, SBPO will continue to use DARPA's SBIR XL pilot, which aims to increase opportunities for DARPA funded
technology by reimagining SBIRs to transform ideas into successful small businesses that scale. The goals of SBIR XL include:
(1) increase relevance of SBIR Program for Technology Development in DARPA; (2) emphasize transition and commercialization
as part of evaluation process including establishment of concrete commercialization milestones; (3) raise award ceilings to support
efforts for operation scale deployment, increasing the probability of technology transition and commercialization; (4) decrease
award timelines.
- Once reauthorized, SBPO will continue to link wherever possible to the OUSD(R&E) Critical Technology Areas which, for FY
2026, include: (1) Applied Artificial Intelligence; (2) Biomanufacturing; (3) Contested Logistics Technologies; (4) Quantum and
Battlefield Information Dominance; (5) Scaled Hypersonics; and (6) Scaled Directed Energy.
- DARPA SBIR/STTR contracting will continue streamlining the acquisition process for Phase II awards and standardizing the
