C. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                                           FY 2025     FY 2026       FY 2027
Title: LongShot                                                                                                                                  64.213          -             -
Description: The LongShot program is developing and flight demonstrating an air-launched system capable of engaging multiple
adversary targets from standoff ranges using existing air-to-air missiles. LongShot will be deployed either externally from existing
fighters or internally from existing bombers. This system will capitalize on a slower speed, fuel-efficient air vehicle for ingress,
while retaining highly energetic air-to-air missiles for end-game target engagements, providing several key benefits that increase
weapon effectiveness. This program will address the stability and control challenges of launching air-to-air missiles from a
relatively small uninhabited system in an operational environment. Potential transition partners include the Navy and Air Force.

Beginning in FY 2026, this program will be funded in PE 0603468E, Project ACX-01.

Title: SPeed and Runway INdependent Technologies (SPRINT) X-Plane Demonstration Project                                                         47.000              -            -
Description: The SPeed and Runway INdependent Technologies (SPRINT) X-Plane Demonstration Project is developing
and demonstrating the fundamental technologies needed for combined high speed and vertical take-off and landing (VTOL)
capabilities in a single aircraft. This program culminates in the fabrication and flight test of a demonstrator that validates the critical
technologies in a representative environment and reduces technical, schedule, and cost risk for a follow-on operational system.
High speed VTOL aircraft are highly desired in a variety of military missions such as contested logistics under attack, infiltration/
exfiltration, electronic warfare, personnel recovery, troop transport, and armed escort. The SPRINT Demonstrator is envisioned to
transition to a Services component for further risk reduction flight testing.

Beginning in FY 2026, this program will be funded in PE 0603468E, Project ACX-01.

Title: Artificial Intelligence (AI) Reinforcements (AIR)                                                                                        51.884              -            -
Description: AI Reinforcements (AIR) is developing and demonstrating dominant tactical autonomy for multi-ship, beyond visual
range (BVR), real-world air combat missions. This program is focused on developing highly accurate models that are orders of
magnitude faster than the present state-of-the-art and then using those models to unlock novel and robust AI-driven autonomy
approaches. An operations-centric development approach will be enabled through the use of human-on-the-loop F-16 aircraft. On
piloted platforms, AIR's algorithms will automate tactical control tasks transforming junior pilots from low-level tacticians into high-
level mission commanders. For unpiloted platforms, AIR will enable vehicles to perform missions with minimal human oversight.
The outcome of this program will be an AI air combat capability that works in dynamic, operationally representative environments.
The transition partner is the U.S. Air Force.

Beginning in FY 2026, this program will be funded in PE 0603468E, Project ACX-01.

C. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                                      FY 2025     FY 2026       FY 2027
Title: Control of Revolutionary Aircraft with Novel Effectors (CRANE)                                                                       18.313          -             -
Description: The Control of Revolutionary Aircraft with Novel Effectors (CRANE) program is developing and demonstrating
revolutionary improvements in aircraft controls technology. The program will design, build, and flight test an aircraft able
to fly and maneuver at altitude relying on state-of-the-art Active Flow Control (AFC) technology. AFC is a broad term that
encompasses a range of technology approaches; it includes a number of control mechanisms which alter the aerodynamic
flow field through ejection or suction of fluid via an orifice on a lifting body. An emphasis of the program is on assessing AFC
component technologies, risk reduction and experimentation, integrated testing, fabrication and demonstration of a relevant scale
novel and innovative aircraft. Technologies, design tools, and models developed and demonstrated under this program will be
made available to all Services as well as the civilian aerospace sector for application to future air systems development.

Beginning in FY 2026, this program will be funded in PE 0603468E, Project ACX-01.

Title: Liberty Lifter                                                                                                                      14.185              -            -
Description: The Liberty Lifter program was intended to design and demonstrate a runway-independent, large-payload,
survivable, dual-flight regime aircraft capable of extended on-water operations and flight both in and out of ground effect.
Critical to an effective aircraft of this type is a robust sea plane capability to operate in high sea states as well as an innovative
manufacturing approach that dramatically reduces vehicle acquisition costs. The vehicle was anticipated to be survivable against
peer threats due to the combination of extremely low altitude operations and speeds significantly higher than ships. The ability to
deploy amphibious cargo while on the water will minimize exposure time and enable a wide variety of mission capabilities in the
maritime domain including rapid contested logistics support, and search and rescue. The Liberty Lifter program was envisioned
to deliver a technology demonstrator with potential to transition to military service partners for continued testing and development
activities. The demonstrator was expected to be approximately 80% size and 50% maximum gross takeoff weight of a future
Liberty Lifter objective system.

Title: AdvaNced airCraft Infrastructure-Less Launch And RecoverY (ANCILLARY)                                                               28.458              -            -
Description: The AdvaNced airCraft Infrastructure-Less Launch And RecoverY (ANCILLARY) program developed and flight
demonstrated an X-plane with the critical technologies required for a leap-ahead in long endurance, vertical takeoff and landing
(VTOL) unmanned air system (UAS) performance. The UAS can launch and recover from small ship flight decks and austere land
locations in adverse weather without additional infrastructure equipment, thus enabling expeditionary deployments. Both the U.S.
Marine Corps and the U.S. Central Command will conduct follow on testing, payload integration, and operations with the aircraft at
the completion of the program.

Title: Rapid Experimental Missionized Autonomy (REMA)                                                                                      13.828              -            -

C. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                                  FY 2025    FY 2026       FY 2027
Description: Commercial-quality drones demonstrate surprising usefulness on the modern battlefield. Rapid Experimental
Missionized Autonomy (REMA) enhanced commercially available and stock military drones with a subsystem to enable
autonomous operation. The program focused on delivering autonomy without being tied to a specific drone design. REMA
developed these capabilities through rapid spirals of development. New mission functionality was delivered through development
spirals accelerating from three-month duration at program inception to one-month by program completion. Legacy drones are
either remotely piloted via radio frequency (RF) tethers or pre-programmed with mission profiles relying on GPS waypoints; neither
approach is ideal for RF-contested environments, hence the need for greater autonomy. Research and Development (R&D)
programs have demonstrated autonomy capabilities for drones, but these have frequently been bespoke solutions, with software
spirals of nine months or longer, too slow of a response in a dynamic battlefield. The REMA program addressed specific challenge
problems, during which performers developed, collaborated, and delivered an autonomy subsystem for drones at a rapid pace.

Title: Advanced Aerospace System Concepts                                                                                               3.614             -            -
Description: Studies conducted under this program examined and evaluated emerging aerospace technologies and system
concepts for applicability to military use. This included the degree and scope of potential impact and improvements to military
operations, mission utility, and warfighter capability. Studies were also conducted to analyze emerging aerospace threats
along with possible methods and technologies to counter them. The feasibility of achieving potential improvements, in terms of
resources, schedule, and technological risk, was also evaluated. The results from these studies were used, in part, to formulate
future prototype development programs or refocus ongoing work. The topics that were researched and analyzed included:
methods of defeating enemy anti-aircraft attacks; munition technologies to increase precision, range, endurance, and lethality of
weapons for a variety of mission sets; novel launch systems; air vehicle control, power, propulsion, materials, and architectures;
and payload and cargo handling systems.

